# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SPEC FILE ORGANIZATION
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

When writing requirement specifications, use hierarchical sections for navigation and readability.

## File Structure Guidelines

**Use 3 levels of markdown headers plus bracketed items:**

### Level 1: Major Areas (# with decorative border)
```
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# DATA DEFINITIONS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
```

Top-level architectural divisions. Typical sections:
- DATA DEFINITIONS
- STATE MANAGEMENT
- CONFIGURATION
- ACTIONS / BEHAVIORS
- COMPONENTS
- INTEGRATIONS
- KEY INSIGHTS

### Level 2: Functional Groups (##)
```
## Session Types
```

Related items grouped by function. Keeps sections under 200 lines.

### Level 3: Sub-groups (### - use sparingly)
```
### Primary Actions
```

Further breakdowns only when Level 2 section would exceed 200 lines.

### Items in Brackets ([Name])
```
[Define SessionMode]
[State SessionManagement]
[Action StartSession]
```

Individual specifications. Always use brackets for parseable structures.

## Recommended Section Order

Follow typical implementation flow:

1. **DATA DEFINITIONS** - Types, enums, constants (vocabulary first)
2. **STATE MANAGEMENT** - What data the system tracks
3. **CONFIGURATION** - Settings, timeouts, environment variables
4. **COMPONENTS** - UI structure (if applicable)
5. **ACTIONS/BEHAVIORS** - What the system does
6. **INTEGRATIONS** - External systems, APIs
7. **KEY INSIGHTS** - Why/how decisions (optional but valuable)

## Organization Example

```toml
# Notification System Specification
Purpose: Send real-time notifications to users via multiple channels

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# DATA DEFINITIONS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Notification Types

[Define NotificationType]
Categories of notifications the system can send

Options:
  - email: Email notification
  - sms: Text message
  - push: Mobile push notification
  - in_app: In-application banner

[Define NotificationPriority]
Urgency level for notification delivery

Options:
  - low: Deliver within 1 hour
  - normal: Deliver within 5 minutes
  - high: Deliver immediately
  - urgent: Deliver immediately with retry

## User Preferences

[Define NotificationPreferences]
User's notification channel preferences

Fields:
  Email enabled: yes/no
  SMS enabled: yes/no
  Push enabled: yes/no
  Quiet hours start: time
  Quiet hours end: time

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STATE MANAGEMENT
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Delivery State

[State NotificationQueue]
Tracks pending notifications for delivery

Data fields:
  Pending notifications: list of Notification
  STATE.processing: yes/no
  Failed deliveries: list with retry count
  Last processed: timestamp

## User State

[State UserNotificationSettings]
Tracks user preferences and opt-out status

Data fields:
  User preferences: NotificationPreferences
  Opted out channels: list of NotificationType
  Last updated: timestamp

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CONFIGURATION
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[Configuration Timeouts]
Delivery attempt timeouts

Values:
  Email delivery timeout: 30 seconds
  SMS delivery timeout: 10 seconds
  Push delivery timeout: 5 seconds
  Retry delay: 5 minutes
  Max retry attempts: 3

[Configuration Providers]
External service configuration

Email provider: SendGrid
SMS provider: Twilio
Push provider: Firebase Cloud Messaging

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ACTIONS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Notification Creation

[Action CreateNotification]
Create new notification for delivery

Input parameters:
  userId: text
  type: NotificationType
  priority: NotificationPriority
  content: text
  metadata: object

Steps:
  - Check user preferences allow this notification type
  - Check not within user's quiet hours
  - Set notification priority
  - Add to notification queue
  - Set STATE.processing: yes

## Notification Delivery

[Action DeliverNotification]
Send notification via appropriate channel

Input parameters:
  notification: Notification object

Steps:
  - Check notification priority
  - Select appropriate provider based on type
  - Call provider API with notification content
  - Wait for delivery confirmation
  - Update delivery status

On success:
  - Remove from queue
  - Save delivery log

On error:
  - Add to failed deliveries
  - Check retry count < max retries
  - If can retry: Schedule retry after delay
  - If max retries reached: Save error details

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# KEY INSIGHTS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[Insight QuietHoursImplementation]
Why we check quiet hours at creation, not delivery

Problem: User sets quiet hours 10pm-8am, notification created at 9:55pm
Challenge: Notification might deliver at 10:05pm during quiet hours

Solution: Check quiet hours when creating notification
  - If within quiet hours: Delay creation until quiet hours end
  - If will enter quiet hours soon: Deliver immediately or wait

Why it matters: Respects user preferences even for queued notifications
```

## Organization Best Practices

**Aim for:**
- 5-10 Level 2 sections per Level 1 section
- Sections under 200 lines (use Level 3 to break up if needed)
- Logical grouping - related items together
- Clear naming - section names describe contents

**Benefits:**
- ✅ Collapsible sections for navigation
- ✅ Outline view shows structure
- ✅ Easy to find specific items
- ✅ Matches implementation flow
- ✅ Reviewable by non-developers (fold technical details)

