## Data Definitions

```toml
[Define EntityName]
Description: Clear explanation of what this represents

Fields:
  fieldName: type (description)
  status: text (Options: active, inactive, pending)
  count: number (Default: 0)
  enabled: yes/no (Default: no)

Source: Database table name or API endpoint
Storage: Where this data persists
```

**Example:**
```toml
[Define UserAccount]
Description: Represents a registered user in the system

Fields:
  email: text (User's email address)
  subscription: text (Options: free, premium, enterprise)
  verified: yes/no (Email verification status)
  lastLogin: timestamp

Source: DB.Users table
Storage: Primary database
```

## State Definitions

```toml
[State ComponentState]
Description: Local state for component behavior

Data fields:
  STATE.loading: yes/no (Default: no)
  STATE.submitting: yes/no (Default: no)
  Error details: text (Default: none)
  Selected item: reference to Item (Default: none)
  Validation results: list of errors (Default: empty)

Lifecycle: Component-scoped
Reset when: Component unmounts
```

**Naming Conventions:**
- Use `STATE.fieldname` for boolean status tracking (loading, submitting, validated, etc.)
- Use descriptive names for data values (Error details, Selected item, User input, etc.)
- Use `reference to Type` for links to other entities

**For Nested State:**
```toml
# Option 1: Flatten boolean states with underscores
STATE.form_has_changes: yes/no
STATE.form_is_valid: yes/no

# Option 2: Group under parent with descriptive names
Form.has changes: yes/no
Form.is valid: yes/no
Form data: {...actual values...}

# Option 3: Use dot notation for clarity (also acceptable)
State.form.hasChanges: yes/no
State.form.isValid: yes/no
```
Choose the pattern that's clearest for your team. The key principle: boolean state tracking should be easily distinguishable from actual data.

